HEADWORD: Bosh
<hw>Bosh</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. G.
<ets>posse</ets> joke, trifle; It. <ets>bozzo</ets> a rough stone,
<ets>bozzetto</ets> a rough sketch, <ets>s-bozzo</ets> a rough draught,
sketch.]</ety> <def>Figure; outline; show.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Bosh</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Bosh
<hw>Bosh</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Turk.]</ety> <def>Empty talk;
contemptible nonsense; trash; humbug.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Bosh</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Bosh
<hw>Bosh</hw>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Boshes</plw>
<pr>(<?/)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[Cf. G. <ets>b⟦oum⟧schung</ets> a
slope.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>One of the sloping sides of the lower part of a
blast furnace; also, one of the hollow iron or brick sides of the bed of
a puddling or boiling furnace.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>The lower part of a blast furnace,
which slopes inward, or the widest space at the top of this
part.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>In forging and smelting, a trough in which tools and
ingots are cooled.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Boshbok</ent>⟦br⟧
